Modular exponentiation

{{task}}
Find the last 40 decimal digits of $a^b$, where

* $a = 2988348162058574136915891421498819466320163312926952423791023078876139$
* $b = 2351399303373464486466122544523690094744975233415544072992656881240319$

<br>
A computer is too slow to find the entire value of $a^b$. 

Instead, the program must use a fast algorithm for <a class="rosetta__link--wiki" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular exponentiation" title="wp: Modular exponentiation">modular exponentiation</a>: $a^b \mod m$.

The algorithm must work for any integers $a, b, m$ <br>where $b \ge 0$ and $m > 0$.
<br><br>


